        <section id="why-comply" class="about section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-title" data-aos="fade-up">
          <h2>Why Comply with the Employment Equity Act?</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="row gy-4" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="100">
          <div class="col-12">
            <p>
              The Employment Equity Act (EE Act) promotes equal opportunity and fair treatment in employment by eliminating unfair discrimination and implementing affirmative action measures. Recent amendments effective 1 January 2025 redefine designated employers and tighten reporting obligations.
            </p>
            <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Who must comply?</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>From 1 January 2025, a designated employer is any organisation that employs 50 or more people. Turnover thresholds no longer apply.</li>
              <li>Smaller employers can voluntarily apply for a compliance certificate if they wish to do business with the state.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Your duties</h3>
            <div class="row g-3">
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <ul class="mb-0">
                  <li>Consult with your employees or trade union representatives.</li>
                  <li>Conduct a workforce analysis to identify barriers and under representation.</li>
                  <li>Prepare a five year Employment Equity Plan that sets numerical targets aligned with government issued sectoral targets.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-md-6">
                <ul class="mb-0">
                  <li>Submit annual EEA2 (employment equity report) and EEA4 (income differentials) forms through the Department of Labour's online portal.</li>
                  <li>Assign senior managers to implement and monitor your plan.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Deadlines for 2025/26</h3>
            <div class="row g-3">
              <div class="col-lg-4"><div class="p-3 border rounded-3 h-100">The 2025 reporting cycle opens on 1 September 2025.</div></div>
              <div class="col-lg-4"><div class="p-3 border rounded-3 h-100">Manual submissions close on 1 October 2025; online submissions remain open until 15 January 2026.</div></div>
              <div class="col-lg-4"><div class="p-3 border rounded-3 h-100">Failure to comply can result in heavy fines, legal action and exclusion from government tenders.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
